      <h1>The Fungi Guide for the Sehome Hill Arboretum</h1>
      <p>
        With roughly 90 species of fungi found in the Arboretum, it’s a
        biodiverse cornucopia! The most prevalent species can be seen with
        little effort, but some hide under shrubs and logs or high up on trees.
Be careful to stick to the trails to minimize damage to undergrowth. A
        lot of important species can be trampled and new growth can’t occur if there is too much traffic outside the clearly marked trails.
      </p>
      <h2><em>Armillaria mellea</em> “Honey Mushroom”</h2>
      <p>
        Honey Mushroom is an umbrella term for a family of mushrooms. The most
        common in the Arboretum is <em> A. Ostoyae</em>. We ask that any Honey
        Mushrooms in the Arboretum are not disturbed, as it can disrupt the
        ecosystem! As the mushroom feeds off white rot, it is almost always
        found at the base of a plant, where it decomposes the roots of a tree or
        plant. The mushroom grows in clusters and around stumps, fallen logs,
        and live plants. Usually, you find them late in the year when the rainy
        season returns. Hallmarks of the Honey Mushroom family are a shadow in
        the center of the cap, and decurrent, or running down the stalk, gills.
      </p>
