      <h2><em>Trametes versicolor</em> “Turkey-tail”</h2>
      <p>
        These flat, fan-shaped mushrooms grow on the sides of logs and trunks.
        The shape and multicolored rings resemble a turkey tail, hence the name.
        Like the Honey Mushroom, the Turkey-tail feeds off white rot and tends
        to be found on dead trees. Playing an important role in decomposition,
        Turkey-tail turns wood’s lignin into a white gooey cellulose. The
        cellulose, which is the main part of a plant’s cell wall, can be
        reabsorbed into the soil, which allows nutrients to reenter the cycle
