      <h2><em>Tremella mesenterica</em> “Witch's Butter”</h2>
      <p>
        Resembling butter, Witch’s Butter goes by many names. The jelly-like
        yellow and orange fungus grows on logs and other dead deciduous wood.
        While considered edible, Witch’s Butter should not be harvested from the
        Arboretum. Witch’s butter is considered a parasite of a parasite and
        consumes a parasite that digests rotting wood. The yellow fungus is just
        a fruiting body and only shows up during warm spells in winter.
      </p>
